<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED0BFF89FF54FAA0FBFFFA98" box="[199,1149,1302,1329]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B534515BED0BFF89FF54FAA0FBFFFA98" blockId="25.[151,1437,1194,2013]" box="[199,1149,1302,1329]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FF54FAA0FECCFA98" bold="true" box="[199,334,1302,1328]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a noun in apposition referring to the 
<typeStatus id="6A30EFF9ED0BFF89FC7FFAA1FB9EFA99" box="[1004,1052,1303,1329]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED0BFF89FF54FA8CFC5FFA34" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B534515BED0BFF89FF54FA8CFC5FFA34" blockId="25.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FF54FA8CFEC0FAFC" bold="true" box="[199,322,1338,1364]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from all congeners by the presence of large lamina on the embolus (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FF0CFAE8FE86FAD0" box="[159,260,1374,1400]" captionStart="FIGURES 134–136" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[291,1301,1009,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-61@27.[277,1311,995,1948]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 134–136. Palp of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in prolateral (134), ventral (136) and retrolateral (135) view, arrow pointing to the ventral lamina of embolus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500821/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 136</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FE83FAE8FEBCFAD0" box="[272,318,1374,1400]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–138" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1364,1388]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,181,1339]" captionTargetId="figure-19@28.[151,1436,181,1341]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 137–138. Palp of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in dorsal (137) and ventral (138) view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500825" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500825/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">138</figureCitation>
). Female resembles 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED0BFF89FDB0FAE8FD5CFAD0" authority="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang, 2022" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[547,734,1374,1400]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asper" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FDB0FAE8FD5CFAD0" box="[547,734,1374,1400]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Charippus asper</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FD75FAE8FCC2FAD0" bold="true" box="[742,832,1374,1400]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED0BFF89FD75FAE8FCC2FAD0" box="[742,832,1374,1400]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the slightly bulging spermathecae with protrusions internally, but can be distinguished by the unique CD path (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FCA2FA34FC52FA34" box="[817,976,1410,1436]" captionStart="FIGURES 139–144" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1524,1548]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-19@29.[151,1436,181,1501]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 139–144. Female genitalia of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 139, 140, 142. Ventral view; 141, 143. Dorsal view; 144. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500827/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 141, 143</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED0BFF8AFF54FA10FE9FFF7D" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="177" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" type="description">
<paragraph id="B534515BED0BFF89FF54FA10FE4CF8AD" blockId="25.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FF54FA10FE26FA68" bold="true" box="[199,420,1446,1472]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Habitus as shown in 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FD06FA10FD74FA68" box="[661,758,1446,1472]" captionStart="FIGURES 128–133" captionStartId="27.[151,264,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 128–133. Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (128, 131) and female (129–130, 132–133). 128-130. Habitus, in dorsal (128–129) and lateral (130) view; 131–132. Front view of carapace; 133. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500819/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
. Carapace length 1.31; abdomen length 0.99. Measurements of eyes: AME 0.27, ALE 0.17, PME 0.04, PLE 0.14. Measurements of legs: I 2.36 (0.73, 0.44, 0.56, 0.35, 0.28), II 1.95 (0.61, 0.31, 0.42, 0.36, 0.25), III 1.86 (0.64, 0.21, 0.35, 0.37, 0.29), IV 1.95 (0.59, 0.24, 0.41, 0.40, 0.31). Chelicerae: dark brown, with fang-like projection distally; promargin with two teeth, retromargin with one bicuspid tooth. Palp (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FEB2F980FE43F9F8" box="[289,449,1590,1616]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 134–136" captionStart-1="FIGURES 137–138" captionStartId-0="27.[151,264,1971,1995]" captionStartId-1="28.[151,264,1364,1388]" captionTargetBox-0="[291,1301,1009,1934]" captionTargetBox-1="[163,1431,181,1339]" captionTargetId-0="figure-61@27.[277,1311,995,1948]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@28.[151,1436,181,1341]" captionTargetPageId-0="27" captionTargetPageId-1="28" captionText-0="FIGURES 134–136. Palp of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in prolateral (134), ventral (136) and retrolateral (135) view, arrow pointing to the ventral lamina of embolus." captionText-1="FIGURES 137–138. Palp of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in dorsal (137) and ventral (138) view." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500821" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500825" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6500821/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6500825/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 134–138</figureCitation>
): embolus short, with large ventral lamina, tip of embolus slightly hooked, with a small triangular process; embolic disc relatively small, not obviously sclerotized; LED narrow, serrulate-edged; tegulum slightly sclerotized, tegular lobe present; retrolateral tibial apophysis thick and wide, inner-curved distally in ventral view. Sternum without setal tuft. Color in alcohol (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FD47F914FCB5F914" box="[724,823,1698,1724]" captionStart="FIGURES 128–133" captionStartId="27.[151,264,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 128–133. Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (128, 131) and female (129–130, 132–133). 128-130. Habitus, in dorsal (128–129) and lateral (130) view; 131–132. Front view of carapace; 133. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500819/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
): carapace reddish brown, CPSB present; dorsal abdomen pale yellow, with dark anchor-shaped marking, not obviously sclerotized; ventral abdomen grayish brown; legs I–II darker than legs III–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B534515BED0BFF8AFF54F8B8FE9FFF7D" blockId="25.[151,1437,1194,2013]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1436,151,250]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="177" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED0BFF89FF54F8B8FEA7F880" bold="true" box="[199,293,1806,1832]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Female.</emphasis>
Habitus as shown in 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FD87F8B8FD33F880" box="[532,689,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURES 128–133" captionStartId="27.[151,264,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 128–133. Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (128, 131) and female (129–130, 132–133). 128-130. Habitus, in dorsal (128–129) and lateral (130) view; 131–132. Front view of carapace; 133. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500819/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 129–130</figureCitation>
. Carapace length 1.11; abdomen length 1.08. Chelicerae (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FAA6F8B8FA16F880" box="[1333,1428,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURES 128–133" captionStartId="27.[151,264,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 128–133. Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (128, 131) and female (129–130, 132–133). 128-130. Habitus, in dorsal (128–129) and lateral (130) view; 131–132. Front view of carapace; 133. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500819/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 133</figureCitation>
) as in male but without fang-like apophysis. Measurements of eyes: AME 0.21, ALE 0.16, PME 0.06, PLE 0.14. Measurements of legs: I 1.54 (0.50, 0.27, 0.33, 0.22, 0.22), II 1.39 (0.47, 0.20, 0.27, 0.25, 0.20), III 1.57 (0.53, 0.23, 0.31, 0.28, 0.22), IV 1.71 (0.54, 0.21, 0.34, 0.37, 0.25). Color in alcohol (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FC5BF8CCFBE5F83C" box="[968,1127,1914,1940]" captionStart="FIGURES 128–133" captionStartId="27.[151,264,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[248,1339,181,850]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 128–133. Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (128, 131) and female (129–130, 132–133). 128-130. Habitus, in dorsal (128–129) and lateral (130) view; 131–132. Front view of carapace; 133. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500819/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 129–130</figureCitation>
): carapace and dorsal abdomen as in male, ventral abdomen pale yellow. Sternum as in male. Epigynum (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FB9CF828FB6AF810" box="[1039,1256,1950,1976]" captionStart="FIGURES 139–144" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1524,1548]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-19@29.[151,1436,181,1501]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 139–144. Female genitalia of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 139, 140, 142. Ventral view; 141, 143. Dorsal view; 144. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500827/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs 139–140, 142</figureCitation>
): window large, rims sclerotized, median septum absent; lateral depressions shallow and not obvious. Vulva (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED0BFF89FB24F874FAE2F874" box="[1207,1376,1986,2012]" captionStart="FIGURES 139–144" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1524,1548]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-19@29.[151,1436,181,1501]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 139–144. Female genitalia of Charippus kubah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 139, 140, 142. Ventral view; 141, 143. Dorsal view; 144. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500827/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 141, 143</figureCitation>
): CD relatively short, swerving for six times; AG small and chilli-like; spermathecae bulging and large, internally with protrusions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED08FF8AFF54FF68FDD2FF52" box="[199,592,222,250]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" type="distribution">
